Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while prior work—such as TOWER in Paper 1—has made strides in improving low-resource parsing through hierarchical, heuristic-driven treebank selection, these methods remain static and non-adaptive. They rely on fixed similarity metrics (e.g., URIEL) and handcrafted thresholds for climbing language hierarchies, which may not generalize well across diverse linguistic typologies or parser architectures. Moreover, Paper 2 highlights that annotation scheme design (UD vs. SUD) affects learnability, suggesting that syntactic structure *quality* is as important as data quantity and proximity. This implies that an optimal training set should not only be large and linguistically similar but also syntactically coherent and structurally learnable. Instead of treating treebank selection as a one-time, rule-based decision, I propose framing it as a dynamic, meta-learned scheduling problem where the model learns *when* and *how much* to sample from which source treebanks based on both typological proximity and structural learnability signals. By making the scheduler differentiable and trainable via reinforcement or gradient-based meta-learning, we enable the system to adaptively balance between exploiting high-similarity sources and exploring potentially beneficial but less obvious ones. This approach diverges from existing work by introducing *trainable*, *continuous* control over data scheduling, fusing multiple heterogeneous signals (typological, syntactic complexity, annotation consistency) into a unified, end-to-end framework. Unlike TOWER’s discrete heuristics or static clustering, our method dynamically adjusts to parser learning dynamics, mitigating overfitting and underfitting risks in low-data regimes.

