  "Idea": "The core idea is to develop a meta-learned, differentiable treebank scheduler that dynamically optimizes training data composition for low-resource dependency parsing by jointly modeling linguistic similarity and syntactic learnability. Rather than using fixed rules or offline clustering to select source treebanks, our approach treats data scheduling as a continuous, learnable process. The scheduler operates as a neural module that assigns soft weights to candidate treebanks at each training step, based on two fused signals: (1) typological proximity (e.g., genealogical, areal, and syntactic features from databases like WALS or URIEL), and (2) syntactic learnability indicators derived from the target language's partial parses or proxy tasks (e.g., transition entropy, label imbalance, head distribution skew). These weights are optimized via a meta-objective that maximizes parsing performance on a small development set of the target language—or, when unavailable, through cross-treebank validation proxies. The scheduler is trained end-to-end with the parser using policy gradients or implicit differentiation, enabling it to discover non-intuitive combinations of source data that outperform hand-designed heuristics. Crucially, the framework incorporates uncertainty-aware exploration, allowing it to escape local optima in data selection (e.g., avoiding over-reliance on a single dominant donor language). This method addresses key limitations in current approaches: (i) rigidity of rule-based selection, (ii) inability to adapt to parser convergence dynamics, and (iii) neglect of annotation scheme quality and structural coherence. By unifying data selection and model training into a single adaptive pipeline, this work advances the paradigm from 'select-then-train' to 'learn-while-selecting', offering a scalable solution for truly low-resource scenarios where even development data is absent. The impact extends beyond parsing to other NLP tasks involving cross-lingua